statement:
\textbf{Short-Answer Question. Simplify your answer as much as possible
and show your work.}

Let $\displaystyle s = f(t) = t^3 - \frac{21}2t^2 + 30t$ be the position
function of a particle that is moving in a straight line, where \emph{t}
is measured in seconds and \emph{s} in metres. When is the particle
moving in the negative direction?

hints:
When the particle is moving in the \emph{negative direction}
(backwards), what function of time is \emph{negative}? (It is not
position!)
